nRevisions","id":"39358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 49-year-old man presents to the emergency department with muscle aches, headache, and non-productive cough. He recently returned from visiting his relatives in Far North Queensland and recalls showering in a nearby creek during his visit. The onset of his symptoms occurred one week after returning from the trip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 126/84 mmHg, pulse 120/min and temperature 38.7\u00b0C.  His eye examination is shown (Image). He has no rashes. His urinalysis shows mild proteinuria and pyuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigation results are as followed:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 130 g/L (120-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC: 20.0 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0\u201311.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPLT: 296 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150\u2013450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELFT: Mildly elevated aminotransferases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiemsa-stained blood smears: Normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis A","Malaria","Dengue fever","Leptospirosis","Typhoid fever"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely suffering from \u003Cstrong\u003Eleptospirosis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is one of the most common zoonotic diseases worldwide. Humans can become infected through contact with infected animals, most commonly rodents, or through contact with soil or water that has been contaminated by the urine of infected animals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for leptospirosis infections include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eoccupational activities such as farming or sewer work\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erecreational exposures, such as freshwater sports or fishing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Econtact with floodwaters\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incubation phase typically ranges from 7 to 12 days. Patients usually present with a sudden onset of fever and headache, with myalgias that are often localised to the calves and lower back. Conjunctival suffusion (dilatation of conjunctival vessels without purulent exudate) is pathognomonic of leptospirosis. Common laboratory findings include neutrophilia, elevated ESR, and mild elevation of aminotransferases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Edengue \u003C/strong\u003Ecan present similarly to leptospirosis. They are both transmitted by mosquitoes, but are now rarely reported in the Far North Queensland region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDetection of parasites on Giemsa-stained blood smears by light microscopy confirms the diagnosis of malaria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlmost half of the patients with dengue infection develop a macular or maculopapular rash. Leukopenia and thrombocytopenia are very common in dengue infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients infected with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis A \u003C/strong\u003Etypically reports an abrupt onset of nausea, vomiting, anorexia, fever, malaise, and abdominal pain. Dark urine, pale stool, jaundice and pruritus are common signs. Serum aminotransferases are often markedly raised, with ALT levels higher than AST.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETyphoid fever \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by stepwise fever and prominent gastrointestinal manifestations such as diarrhoea or constipation. Relative bradycardia (pulse-temperature dissociation) may be observed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcknowledgements: \u0022\u003Ca href=\u0022https://wikem.org/wiki/File:Conjunctivalsuffusion.jpg\u0022\u003EEye changes after recent travel\u003C/a\u003E\u201d by \u003Ca href=\u0022https://wikem.org/wiki/User:Ostermayer\u0022\u003EDaniel Ostermayer\u003C/a\u003E is licensed under \u003Ca href=\u0022https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\u0022\u003ECC BY 4.0\u003C/a\u003E.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Leptospirosis should be strongly suspected in patients who present with a febrile illness and have a history of exposure to freshwaters or travel to flooded areas.","Conjunctival suffusion (dilatation of conjunctival vessels without purulent exudate) is pathognomonic of leptospirosis."],"references":["Haake DA, Levett PN. Leptospirosis in humans. Curr Top Microbiol Immunol [Internet]. 2014 Nov 12 [cited 2023 Jun 28]:65-97. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4442676/ doi: 10.1007/978-3-662-45059-8_5","Lau CL, Townell N, Stephenson E, Craig SB. Leptospirosis: An important zoonosis acquired through work, play and travel. Aust J Gen Pract [Internet]. 2018 Mar [cited 2023 Jun 28];47(3):105-10. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/march/leptospirosis doi: 10.31128/AFP-07-17-4286"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20207"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20207"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3Jmqumj1gZzFmLqh48NfiXRgwTwB2f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3Jmqumj1gZzFmLqh48NfiXRgwTwB2f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":224}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/